# This function will be useful later on.
makeTable9.3 <- function(thedata, nbest=1){
  
  if (nbest < 1 | nbest > dim(thedata)[2]-1){
    warning("nbest recoded to 1")
    nbest <- 1
  }
  
  cnames <- colnames(thedata)

  Yat <- grep("Y",cnames)
  
  if (length(Yat)>1)
    stop("Currently you have: ", paste(cnames[Yat], ", ", sep=""), 
               " in your data set.\n There can be only one response variable.\n",
               sep="")

  colnames(thedata)[Yat] <- "Y"
  Xat <- grep("X",cnames)
  
  require("leaps")
  require("qpcR")

  reg <- regsubsets(thedata[,Xat],thedata[,Yat], nbest=nbest, nvmax=length(cnames)-1)

  regs <- summary(reg)
  
  models <- sapply(1:length(row.names(regs$which)), function(i){
    colnames(regs$which)[which(regs$which[i,])][-1]
  })
  
  pressdata <<- thedata
  
  PRESS <- sapply(models, function(model){
    tmpf <- formula(paste("Y~",
                          paste(model,
                                c(rep("+",length(model)-1), ""), 
                                sep="", 
                                collapse=""), 
                          sep=""))
    tmp <- lm(tmpf, data=pressdata)
    tmp$call$formula <- eval(tmpf)
    PRESS(tmp, verbose=FALSE)$stat
  })
  
  n <- nrow(thedata)
  p <- as.numeric(row.names(regs$which))+1
 
  
  AIC <- regs$bic-log(n)*p-2*p

  
  AIC2 <- sapply(models, function(model){
    tmpf <- formula(paste("Y~",
                          paste(model,
                                c(rep("+",length(model)-1), ""), 
                                sep="", 
                                collapse=""), 
                          sep=""))
    tmp <- lm(tmpf, data=pressdata)
    tmp$call$formula <- eval(tmpf)
    AIC(tmp)
  })
  
  tmp <- data.frame(p=p, 
             model= sapply(1:length(models), function(i) {
                      paste(models[[i]], collapse=",")
                    }),
             SSEp=regs$rss,
             R2p=regs$rsq,
             R2ap=regs$adjr2,
             Cp=regs$cp,
             AICp=AIC2,
             SBCp=regs$bic,
             PRESSp=PRESS)
  
  rbind(data.frame(p=1,
                   model="(intercept)",
                   SSEp=regs$rss[1]/(1-regs$rsq[1]),
                   R2p=0,
                   R2ap=0,
                   Cp=NA,
                   AICp=NA,
                   SBCp=NA,
                   PRESSp=NA),tmp)
}

a) Using only first-order terms for the predictor variables in the pool of potential X variables, find the four best subset regression models according to the \(R^{2}_{a,p}\) criterion.

Solution: 
makeTable9.3(p9.10, 4) %>% 
  group_by(p) %>% 
  top_n(1, R2ap) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  slice(2:n()) %>% 
  dplyr::select(model, R2ap) %>% 
  pander::pander()
model R2ap

X1,X3 0.9269
X1,X3,X4 0.956

b) Since there is relatively little difference in \(R^{2}_{a,p}\) for the four best subset models, what other criteria would you use to help in the selection of the best model? Discuss.

Solution:
You can use domain knoweldge and validation, this is something we havent learned about yet, but obviously if some variables really have no business being in the model (for ethicial or non-related reasons) then we could choose to drop those variables. Honestly, when looking at a model it might be usefull to think about what kind of data will be easy to collect later in order to use the model.
